{"source":"user-event","type":"click","text":"Chapter 02 — Revenue Landscape\n      \n      Service Charge Revenue Tells a Different Story Than Fee Schedules\n\n      \n        \n          \n            Fee Prices\n            YoY Change\n          \n          \n            Flat\n            0.0%\n          \n          Median across 6 spotlight categories\n        \n        \n          \n            Revenue\n            YoY Change\n          \n          \n            $7.2B\n            +4.2%\n          \n          FFIEC Call Reports, Q1 2026\n        \n      \n\n      \n        Published fee amounts suggest remarkable stability across American banking. The median overdraft fee has held at $29.00 for three consecutive quarters. NSF fees remain anchored at $25.00.\n      \n      \n        But Call Report data tells a different story. Aggregate service charge revenue on deposit accounts reached $7.2 billion in Q1, up 4.2% year-over-year. The divergence points to transaction volume — not pricing — as the primary revenue growth engine.\n      \n\n      \n      \n        Key Finding\n        Eight of twelve Federal Reserve districts report rising consumer delinquencies, suggesting overdraft volume growth may accelerate through year-end.\n      \n\n      \n        For bank executives, the implication is clear: fee schedule stability masks growing revenue sensitivity to economic conditions. Institutions in districts with elevated financial stress should prepare for regulatory scrutiny of overdraft practices.\n      \n\n      Bank Fee Index  |  National Quarterly Report — Q2 2026     7","choice":"c","id":null,"timestamp":1775570608822}
